@edition "2026.6"

-- D1(ix) frontier guardrail. This program is VALID (it type-checks clean — a `_test`,
-- not a `_bad`), but it uses the short-circuit boolean `&&`. eval evaluates it (lazy
-- in the right operand); the compute spine only lowers the STRICT arithmetic/comparison
-- PrimOps, and `&&`/`||`/`|>` need control flow (lazy evaluation of the second operand,
-- or a first-class pipeline) the lowerer does not yet emit — so `BinOp '&&'` is refused.
-- The differential harness must report it `unsupported` — a CLEAN refusal at the
-- compiler frontier — never a miscompile, never a JS crash.
--
-- This is the backend-slice analogue of a `_bad` twin: a backend slice adds no checker
-- rejection rule, so the guarantee under test is "the compiler refuses what it cannot
-- yet lower, loudly", asserted by the harness rather than by an error count. D1(ii)
-- moved the frontier PAST scalar `match`; D1(iii) PAST tuples; D1(iv) PAST ADT
-- constructors; D1(v) PAST records; D1(vi) PAST lists; D1(vii) PAST closures-as-values;
-- D1(viii) PAST first-class `def` references; D1(ix) PAST first-class BUILTIN references
-- — a builtin bound, passed, and displayed `<fn:name>` (see compile_builtinref_test).
-- The frontier now sits at SHORT-CIRCUIT booleans — `&&` (and its kin `||`, `|>`). This
-- file uses one, so it still refuses; when short-circuit lowering lands (a later D1
-- slice, as a lazy `if`), it flips from `unsupported` to a print with no edit.

def main(): Effect [io] ()
  let b = true && false
  println(b)
